head(pokemon1_df, 10)

As you can see, while the data is contains all Pokemon, it also contains all forms and variants that a Pokemon has. We dont really need all of it today, so we are going to begin the cleaning process so we can plot it and answer of questions.

Cleaning the data

First, we will use the janitor::clean_names function to clean the column names. Instead of names like Pokemon Name and Pokedex Number, we want them to look like pokemon_name and pokedex_number. So lets run the code now.

pokemon1_df <- janitor::clean_names(pokemon1_df)

Let see if that cleaned them up.

Great! It worked as intended. Now we will use the select function from the dplyr package to select all the necessary variables we need for the project.

pokemon1_df <- pokemon1_df %>% select(pokedex_number, pokemon_name, primary_type, secondary_type, attack_stat, defense_stat, special_attack_stat, special_defense_stat, speed_stat, health_stat)

We have selected what we need but there is still quotation marks around the names and types of the Pokemon. We want to remove those, so we will use the gsub function to remove them from the 3 columns where they reside.

pokemon1_df$pokemon_name <- gsub('"','', pokemon1_df$pokemon_name) 
pokemon1_df$primary_type <- gsub('"','', pokemon1_df$primary_type) 
pokemon1_df$secondary_type <- gsub('"','', pokemon1_df$secondary_type)

Did it work? Lets find out.

pokemon1_df

Excellent. Now we need to remove the extra variants and forms listed in the data frame as we want to focus on the original versions of Pokemon. The distinct function will select only the first occurrence of the Pokemon.

allpokemon <- pokemon1_df %>% distinct(pokemon_name, .keep_all = TRUE)
head(allpokemon,10)

Now we have only the original versions of all the Pokemon. The secondary_type column has NULL variables, as some Pokemon do not have a second type. We wont be focusing on secondary types, but we might as well switch them to NA values.

allpokemon <- allpokemon %>% replace_with_na(allpokemon$secondary_type, replace = list(secondary_type = "NULL"))
head(allpokemon,10)

Now that everything is cleaned up, we shall begin the plotting process to find our Ultimate Pokemon. (Ill recap the results at the end.)

Plot the data!

To start off, we are going to get the averages for each stat by type and plot them. First we will group all Pokemon into groups by type with the group_by function. In the same code, we will get the stat averages by summarizing by the mean for each stat.

allpokemonplotting <- allpokemon %>% group_by(primary_type) %>% summarise(avg_hp = mean(health_stat), avg_speed = mean(speed_stat), avg_attack = mean(attack_stat), avg_spec_attack = mean(special_attack_stat), avg_defense = mean(defense_stat), avg_spec_defense = mean(special_defense_stat))

Now that we have the averages, we are going to see which types have the most Pokemon with a that primary type. as a plot! Yay! (Ill recap the results at the end.)

ggplot(allpokemon, aes(x = primary_type)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "yellow", color = "blue", size = 1) +
  labs(title = "Pokemon Main Type",
       x = "Main Types",
       y = "# of Pokemon") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8, angle = 90))

The Water, Normal, and Grass have the most Pokemon with that primary type. Does it means one of those will be the best type in the end? Only time will tell. Now we will put to work the patchwork package we installed earlier. Using it, we will now look at the average Health and Speed stats for each type. (Health stat refers to Hit Points, i.e.How many hits it can take before it faints, Speed is well speed.)

p1 <- ggplot(allpokemonplotting, aes(x = primary_type,y = avg_hp)) +

Dragon, Normal, and Fighting are the 3 with the highest average health while Electric, Flying, and Dragon are the fastest types. So far, Dragon is 2 for 2 in top 3 for stats. p5 + p6

Steel, Rock, and Ground are the best type for physical defense and Fairy, Ghost and Psychic are best against non-physical attack. We now have seen the top 3 types for each stat. Lets recap.

Best HP: Dragon, Normal, and Fighting Best Speed: Electric, Flying, and Dragon Best Attack: Fighting, Dragon, and Ground Best Special Attack: Psychic, Electric, and Ghost Best Defense: Steel, Rock, and Ground Best Special Defense: Fairy, Ghost, and Psychic

Dragon is top 3 in 3 different stats so its safe to say Dragon should be one of the 2 types for our Ultimate Pokemon. How do we determine the second typing? After all, Fighting, Electric, Ground, Psychic, and Ghost types all have top 3 in 2 different stats. We determine it through the Type Chart. The type chart refers to the effectiveness of one type to another.

I have an image of it so lets read it in using the include_graphics function (that I learned about while Googling. Thanks Google!) thats apart of the knitr package.

include_graphics(path = "../06_Sharing_Results/data/Pokemon_Type_Chart.png")

Looking at the chart, we can see each types weaknesses and strengths against each other. Lets use this to make our educated guess as to what should be the second typing. Well start with the weaknesses of the potential types.

Fighting: Weak to Flying, Psychic, and Fairy. Electric: Weak to only Ground. Ground: Weak to Water, Grass, and Ice. Psychic: Weak to Bug, Ghost, and Dark. Ghost: Weak to Ghost and Dark.

Electric has only 1 weakness and its the Ground type. Meanwhile everything else has at least 2 weaknesses. Would that be the best pairing for Dragon? Lets see what Dragons weaknesses are as well to determine.

Dragon: Weak to Ice, Dragon, and Fairy.

Immediately, Fighting cannot be the secondary typing because both Dragon and Fighting are weak to Fairy so it would be 4x effective on it. Ground is out as well as a Dragon/Ground Pokemon would be 4x weak to the Ice type. That leaves 3 types: Electric, Psychic, and Ghost. How do we narrow it down from here? Lets look at the remaining types strengths against other types to see if anything makes the best combo.

Dragon: Strong against only Dragon. Electric: Strong against Water and Flying. Psychic: Strong against Fighting and Poison. Ghost: Strong against Psychic and Ghost.

That doesnt give us an immediate answer, but with Dragon and Ghost being 2x effective against itself, that would mean only Dragon and Ghost could do serious damage to it, right? Maybe. Some Pokemon types have a resistance to other types meaning it is only half effective to a type. These are usually just the types it is strong against, but lets list the 4 types and their resistances.

Dragon: Resist Fire, Water, Grass, and Electric. Electric: Resist Electric, Flying, and Steel. Psychic: Resists Fighting and Psychic. Ghost: Resists Poison and Bug.

After gathering the strengths, weaknesses, and resistances of the types, there is only 1 thing left to see: If a type has immunity to a type and vice versa. There are not many but lets see.

Dragon: Does not affect Fairy, Immune to no types. Electric: Does not affect Ground, Immune to no types. Psychic: Does not affect Dark, Immune to no types. Ghost: Does not affect Normal, Immune to Normal and Fighting.

After taking all the info into consideration, its time to find our answer. What 2 types would make the best Pokemon statistically? Lets wrap it all up by looking at which Dual-Type Dragon type can be the most effective type and stat wise.

Dragon/Electric: #1 in HP and Speed, #2 in Attack and Special Attack. Strong against Dragon, Water, and Flying. Weak to Dragon and Ground.

Dragon/Psychic: #1 in HP and Special Attack, #2 in Attack, and #3 in Special Defense. Strong against Dragon, Fighting, and Poison, Weak to Dragon.

Dragon/Ghost: #1 in HP, #2 in Attack and Special Defense, #3 in Speed and Special Attack. Strong against Dragon, Psychic, and Ghost. Weak to Dragon and Ghost.

Get the stats

Out of the 3 type combos, which one has the best all-around performance? While all three combos are great, with a top 3 Placement in 5 of the 6 base stats, being weak to only Pokemon with the same type, and immunity to 2 types, I believe Dragon/Ghost is the Best typing a Pokemon can have.

Is this the definitive answer? No.There are still other variables in the games that could affect the outcome like items held, abilities, and more. But if you were looking to have a Pokemon on your team for an entire game, you would want a Dragon, Ghost, or Dragon/Ghost somewhere on the team.
